text="The role of interchange in diagrammatic reasoning">The role of interchange in <fr:link
href="jms-00B8.xml"
title="String diagrams"
addr="jms-00B8"
type="local">diagrammatic reasoning</fr:link></fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>In a 2-category, interchange is strict; in particular, this means that vertical composition and horizontal composition commute strictly with each other. This is very useful for <fr:link
href="jms-00B8.xml"
title="String diagrams"
addr="jms-00B8"
type="local">string diagrams</fr:link>, but it is not strictly necessary. In a <fr:link
href="jms-00B8.xml"
title="String diagrams"
addr="jms-00B8"
type="local">string diagram</fr:link>, strict interchange means that 2-cells can be freely moved upward and downward; so if you want to use diagrammatic reasoning to study something in a structure that has only weak interchange, you need two things:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>The vertical position of a 2-cell is fixed.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>No two 2-cells should appear at the same vertical position.</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>To move a 2-cell up or down is to insert an interchange cell. It is this principle that makes <fr:link
href="jms-00BG.xml"
title="Homotopy.io"
addr="jms-00BG"
type="local"><fr:code>homotopy.io</fr:code></fr:link> work.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
